On the other hand, the tribological performances of O-CQDs-N at different concentration in PAO were showed in the Fig. 10
                        . The addition of O-CQDs-N changed the evolution of friction coefficient with time lubricated by PAO and increased the coefficient of friction. Before adding O-CQDs-N, the base oil molecules of PAO absorbed on the surface and a low shear stress oil film formed due to the comb-branched chains. Once the O-CQDs-N was added, the polar groups such as amide, hydroxyl and carboxyl facilitated the absorption of O-CQDs-N on the surface, thus forming a relatively higher shear stress oil film or oil film with a higher surface roughness, which dominated the tribological properties and increased friction coefficient [30]. However, it was obvious that O-CQDs-N as the additive to PAO exhibited anti-wear property as Fig. 10b shown. The addition of O-CQDs-N at merely 0.1 wt% to PAO reduced the WSD to 0.684 mm (by 21.3%). When the concentration of O-CQDs-N increased to 2 wt%, the WSD was still much smaller than that of PAO. The optimum addition was 0.5 wt% of which the WSD was 0.621 mm (reduced by 28.5%). Although 3D images (Fig. 11
                        ) detected some furrows and scratches on the worn surface lubricated by PAO with 0.5 wt% O-CQDs-N, the wear scar was much smaller and shallower than that lubricated by PAO. As for the tribological influence of OA in PAO, it found that wear scar diameter was 0.675 mm (reduced by 22.3%) in figure S1, which was still larger than that of 0.5 wt% O-CQDs-N. The result showed that the anti-wear performance of O-CQDs-N stemmed in part from the formation of protective film of OA.
